<P ID=PARA2869 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2870 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company repurchases its common stock from time to time on the open market or in other transactions and holds such shares as treasury stock. The Company presents the cost to repurchase treasury stock as a reduction of stockholders&#8217; equity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2871 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2872 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	From time to time, the Company reissues treasury stock under its employee stock purchase plan and equity incentive plans, upon purchases or exercises of equity awards under the plans. When treasury stock is reissued, the Company accounts for the re-issuance in accordance with ASC No. 505-30, &#8220;Treasury Stock&#8221; and charges the excess of the purchase cost over the re-issuance price (loss) to retained earnings. The purchase cost is calculated based on the specific identification method. In case the purchase cost is lower than the re-issuance price, the Company credits the difference to additional paid-in capital.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2873 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<TABLE ID=MTAB2875 STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF; WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-INDENT: 0PX" CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 57PT">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 28PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
<P ID=PARA2876 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	x.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
<P ID=PARA2877 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Investment in other company:
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P ID=PARA2878 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2879 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Investment in other company is stated at cost. The Company followed ASC 323, &#8220;Investments - Equity and Joint Ventures,&#8221; to determine whether it should apply the equity method of accounting to a certain investment in preferred shares, and determined that the preferred shares were not in substance common stock.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2880 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2881 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company&#8217;s investment in other company is reviewed for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of such investment may not be recoverable, in accordance with ASC 325-20. As of December 31, 2014, no impairment loss was indicated. As of December 31, 2015, an impairment in the amount of $400 was recognized in the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements as a result of the expiration of a purchase option related to such investment. (See also Note 9).
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA76.1 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV ID=PGBK76 STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0PT; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0PT">
<DIV ID=PGFTR76 STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER">
	&nbsp;
</DIV>
<DIV ID=PGNUM76 STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER">
	-73-
</DIV>
<HR STYLE="HEIGHT: 2PX; WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS; COLOR: #000000" NOSHADE>
<A NAME="eolPage76"></A>
<DIV ID=PGHDR76 STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT">
	&nbsp;
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P ID=PARA76.2 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
</FONT>
</P>
<TABLE ID=MTAB2884 STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF; WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-INDENT: 0PX" CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 57PT">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 28PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
<P ID=PARA2885 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	y.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
<P ID=PARA2886 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Recently Issued Accounting Guidance:
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P ID=PARA2887 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2888 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-LEFT: 81PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	In May 2014, FASB issued ASU 2014-09, "Revenue from Contracts with Customers." ASU 2014-09 modifies revenue recognition guidance for U.S. GAAP. Previous revenue recognition guidance in U.S. GAAP comprised broad revenue recognition concepts together with numerous revenue requirements for particular industries or transactions, which sometimes resulted in different accounting for economically similar transactions. In contrast, International Accounting Standards Board ("IASB") provided limited guidance on revenue recognition. Accordingly, the FASB and IASB initiated a joint project to clarify the principles for recognizing revenue and to develop a common revenue standard for GAAP and International Financial Reporting Standards ("IFRS"). The core principle of the guidance is that an entity should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. To achieve that core principle, an entity should apply the following steps:&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2889 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2890 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-LEFT: 81PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Step 1: Identify the contract(s) with a customer.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2891 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 101.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; TEXT-INDENT: -20.7PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2892 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-LEFT: 81PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Step 2: Identify the performance obligations in the contract.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2893 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 101.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; TEXT-INDENT: -20.7PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2894 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-LEFT: 81PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Step 3: Determine the transaction price.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2895 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-LEFT: 81PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2896 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-LEFT: 81PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Step 4: Allocate the transaction price to the performance obligations in the contract.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2897 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-LEFT: 81PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2898 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-LEFT: 81PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Step 5: Recognize revenue when (or as) the entity satisfies a performance obligation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; TEXT-INDENT: -20.7PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P ID=PARA2899 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-LEFT: 81PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	In August 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-14 to defer the effective date of ASU 2014-09 by one year. As a result, the amendments in ASU 2014-09 are effective for annual reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2017, including interim periods within that reporting period. Early adoption is permitted only as of annual reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2016, including interim periods within that reporting period. An entity shall adopt the amendments in ASU 2014-09 by either (i) retrospectively adjusting each prior reporting period presented or (ii) retrospectively adjusting for the cumulative effect of initially applying ASU 2014-09 at the date of initial adoption. The Company has not determined (i) the extent to which it expects ASU 2014-09 will impact its reported revenues or (ii) the manner in which it will adopt ASU 2014-09.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In September 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-16, "Business Combinations." ASU 2015-16 modifies how changes to provisional amounts determined during the measurement period of a business combination are recognized. Under existing accounting literature, changes to provisional amounts determined during the measurement period of a business combination, resulting from facts and circumstances that existed on the acquisition date, are recognized by retrospectively adjusting the provisional amounts on the acquisition date. However, under ASU 2015-16, an acquirer recognizes adjustments to provisional amounts that are identified during the measurement period in the reporting period in which the adjustments are determined. ASU 2015-16 is effective for annual reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2015, including interim periods within that reporting period.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA343.1 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV ID=PGBK343 STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0PT; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0PT">
<DIV ID=PGFTR343 STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER">
	&nbsp;
</DIV>
<DIV ID=PGNUM343 STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER">
	-74-
</DIV>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	U.S. dollars in thousands, except share and per share data.
</B>
	&nbsp;

	The actual maturity dates may differ from the contractual maturities because debtors may have the right to call or prepay obligations without penalties.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2998 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA2999 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 55PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The total fair value of marketable securities with outstanding unrealized losses as of December 31, 2015 amounted to $84,095, while the unrealized losses for these marketable securities amounted to $534. Of the $534 unrealized losses outstanding as of December 31, 2015, a portion of which in the amount of $70 was related to marketable securities that were in a loss position for more than 12 months and the remaining portion of $464 was related to marketable securities that were in a loss position for less than 12 months.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3000 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3001 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 55PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The total fair value of marketable securities with outstanding unrealized losses as of December 31, 2014 amounted to $68,945, while the unrealized losses for these marketable securities amounted to $410. Of the $410 unrealized losses outstanding as of December 31, 2014, a portion of which in the amount of $113 was related to marketable securities that were in a loss position for more than 12 months and the remaining portion of $297 was related to marketable securities that were in a loss position for less than 12 months.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3002 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 55PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3003 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Management believes that as of December 31, 2015, the unrealized losses in the Company&#8217;s investments in all types of marketable securities were temporary and no impairment loss was realized in the Company&#8217;s consolidated statements of operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA79.1 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	U.S. dollars in thousands, except share and per share data.
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
</FONT>
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P ID=PARA3005 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 55PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The unrealized losses related to the Company&#8217;s marketable securities were primarily due to changes in interest rates. Because the Company does not intend to sell the investments and it is not more likely than not that the Company will be required to sell the investments before recovery of their amortized cost bases, which may be maturity, the Company does not consider those investments to be other-than-temporarily impaired at December 31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA78.1 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
</FONT>

<P ID=PARA3007 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 55PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Proceeds from maturity of available-for-sale marketable securities during 2015, 2014 and 2013 were $20,127, $23,250 and $18,325, respectively. Proceeds from sales of available-for-sale marketable securities during 2015, 2014 and 2013 were $13,238, $46,491 and $42,949, respectively. Realized gains from the sale of available-for sale marketable securities for 2015, 2014 and 2013 were $3, $73 and $1,013, respectively. Realized losses from the sale of available-for sale marketable securities for 2015, 2014 and 2013 were $27, $12 and $4, respectively. The Company determines realized gains or losses on the sale of available-for-sale marketable securities based on a specific identification method.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	NOTE 8:-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; F
</FONT>
</B>
<B>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	AIR VALUE MEASUREMENTS
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3168 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3169 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	In accordance with ASC 820, the Company measures its cash equivalents, marketable securities and foreign currency derivative contracts at fair value. Cash equivalents, marketable securities and foreign currency derivative contracts are classified within Level 1 or Level 2 value hierarchies. This is because cash equivalents, and marketable securities are valued using quoted market prices or alternative pricing sources and models utilizing market observable inputs. Foreign currency derivative contracts are classified within Level 2 value hierarchy as the valuation inputs are based on quoted prices and market observable data of similar instruments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3170 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3171 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">

</FONT>
</P>

	&nbsp;

<P ID=PARA3260 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.9PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	In addition to the assets and liabilities described above, the Company&#8217;s financial instruments also include cash and cash equivalents, restricted deposits, short term deposits, trade receivables, other accounts receivable, trade payables, accrued expenses and other payables. The fair value of these financial instruments was not materially different from their carrying value at December 31, 2015 and 2014 due to the short-term maturity of these instruments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3262 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">

<P ID=PARA228 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-LEFT: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	NOTE 9:-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	INVESTMENT IN OTHER COMPANY
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3267 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
</FONT>
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P ID=PARA3272 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	On October 24, 2013, the Company made an investment of $2,200 in a private company in Asia. The investment was in return for approximately 14% of the equity of the company, on a fully diluted basis. The Company also signed an agreement pursuant to which it had the option to purchase all of the remaining outstanding securities of the private company by no later than December 31, 2014. The terms and conditions of the investment were modified on November 2014, including an extension of the option to purchase the remaining outstanding securities until December 31, 2015. The investment is accounted under the cost-method in accordance with ASC 325-20.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3273 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3274 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company did not exercise the purchase option by December 31, 2015 and as a result, recorded a write-off in the amount of $400.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3275 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<P ID=PARA3310 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3311 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.9PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	As of December 31, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	and 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	, the defined benefits plans that the Company assumed in connection with the CIPT Acquisition that are accounted for in the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements are the pension plans in Germany and India. Consistent with the requirements of local law, the Company deposits funds for certain plans with insurance companies, third-party trustees, or into government-managed accounts, and/or accrues for the unfunded portion of the obligation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3312 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3313 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.9PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company&#8217;s pension obligation in Germany relating to the unvested pension claims (i.e. future obligation that will result from future service period) of the employees were outsourced in November 2010 to an external insurance company (&#8220;Nuremberger Versicherung&#8221;). From and after the outsourcing date, the Company is required to pay premiums to the external insurance company and in return the pension benefits earned by the German employees are covered by the Company&#8217;s arrangement with the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	external insurance company. The Company legally is released from its obligations to the German employees once the premiums are paid, and it is no longer subject to any of the risks and rewards associated with the benefit obligations covered and the plan assets transferred to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	the external insurance company. Since the outsourcing arrangement meets the requirements of a nonparticipating annuity contract, the Company treats the costs of the outsourcing arrangement as the costs of the benefits being earned in accordance with ASC Paragraph 715-30-25-7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	of ASC 715 &#8220;Compensation&#8212;Retirement Benefits.&#8221;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3314 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3315 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.9PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">

	The following tables provide a reconciliation of the changes in the pension plans&#8217; benefit obligation and fair value of assets for the years ended December 31, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	and 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	, and the statement of funded status as of December 31, 2015
</FONT>

</B>

	&nbsp;

<P ID=PARA3383 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.9PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The amounts reported for net periodic pension costs and the respective benefit obligation amounts are dependent upon the actuarial assumptions used. The Company reviews historical trends, future expectations, current market conditions, and external data to determine the assumptions. The discount rate is determined considering the yield of government bonds. The rate of compensation increase is determined by the Company, based on its long-term plans for such increases.
</FONT>
</P>

<P ID=PARA3525 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.9PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	Valuation techniques -
</B>
	For Level 2 inputs, the Company utilizes quoted market prices in markets that are not active, broker or dealer quotations, or alternative pricing sources with reasonable levels of price transparency.
</FONT>

<P ID=PARA91.2 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<P ID=PARA316 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; MARGIN: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	U.S. dollars in thousands, except share and per share data.
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
</FONT>
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P ID=PARA3528 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Regarding the policy for amortizing actuarial gains or losses for pension and post-employment plans, the Company has chosen the &#8220;corridor&#8221; option. This option consists of recognizing in the consolidated statements of operations, the part of unrecognized actuarial gains or losses exceeding 10% of the greater of the PBO or the market value of the plan assets. If amortization is required, the minimum amortization amount is that excess divided by the average remaining service period of the active employees expected to receive benefits under the plan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3529 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3530 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; TEXT-INDENT: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
</B>
	Actuarial profits were recognized in other comprehensive income (loss) in the amount of $63 for the year ended December 31, 2015. Actuarial losses were recognized in other comprehensive income (loss) in the amount of $209 and $11 for the years ended December 31, 2014 and 2013, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>

Subject to the rights of holders of preferred stock, if any, in the event of liquidation, dissolution or winding up, holders of common stock are entitled to share ratably in all of the Company&#8217;s assets. The Company&#8217;s Board of Directors may declare a dividend out of funds legally available therefore and, subject to the rights of holders of preferred stock, if any, the holders of common stock are entitled to receive ratably any such dividends.

	Stock purchase plan and equity incentive plans:
</FONT>
</P>

<P ID=PARA3630 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3631 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company has various equity incentive plans under which employees, officers, non-employee directors of the Company and its subsidiaries and others, including consultants, may be granted rights to purchase the Company&#8217;s common stock. The plans authorize the administrator, except for the grant of RSUs, to grant equity incentive awards at an exercise price of not less than 100% of the fair market value of the common stock on the date the award is granted. It is the Company&#8217;s policy to grant stock options and SARs at an exercise price that equals the fair market value
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA93.1 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">

</DIV>
<DIV ID=PGNUM93 STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER">
	-84-
</DIV>
<HR STYLE="HEIGHT: 2PX; WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS; COLOR: #000000" NOSHADE>
<A NAME="eolPage87"></A>
<DIV ID=PGHDR93 STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT">
	&nbsp;
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P ID=PARA93.2 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA314 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; MARGIN: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	U.S. dollars in thousands, except share and per share data.
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
</FONT>
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P ID=PARA3633 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Equity awards granted under all stock incentive plans that are cancelled or forfeited before expiration become available for future grant.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3634 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 76.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3635 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Until the end of 2012, the Company granted to employees and executive officers of the Company primarily share appreciation rights (&#8220;SARs&#8221;), capped with a ceiling, under the various equity incentive plans. The SAR unit confers the holder the right to stock appreciation over a preset price of the Company&#8217;s common stock during a specified period of time. When the unit is exercised, the appreciation amount is paid through the issuance of shares of the Company&#8217;s common stock. The ceiling limits the maximum income for each SAR unit and the maximum number of shares to be issued. SARs are considered an equity instrument as it is a net share settled award capped with a ceiling.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3636 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 76.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3637 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Starting in 2013, the Company granted to employees and executive officers of the Company primarily restricted stock units (&#8220;RSUs&#8221;) under the various equity incentive plans. An RSU award is an agreement to issue shares of our common stock at the time the award is vested. RSUs granted to employees and executive officers generally
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	vest over a four year period from the grant date with 25% of the RSUs granted vesting on the first anniversary of the grant date and 6.25% vesting each quarter thereafter.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3638 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 76.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3639 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	A summary of the various plans is as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3640 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3641 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	1993 Director Stock Option Plan
</B>
<B>
	(Directors Plan)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3642 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 76.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3643 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Upon the closing of the Company&#8217;s initial public offering, the Company adopted the Directors Plan. Under the Directors Plan, which expired in January 2014, the Company was authorized to issue nonqualified stock options to the Company&#8217;s outside non-employee directors to purchase up to 1,980,875 shares of common stock at an exercise price equal to the fair market value of the common stock on the date of grant. The Directors Plan, as amended, provided that each person who became an outside, non-employee director of the Board of Directors was automatically granted an option to purchase 30,000 shares of common stock (the &#8220;First Option&#8221;). Thereafter, each outside director was automatically granted an option to purchase 15,000 shares of common stock (a &#8220;Subsequent Option&#8221;) on January 1 of each year if, on such date, he had served on the Board of Directors for at least six months. In addition, an option to purchase an additional 15,000 shares of common stock (a &#8220;Committee Option&#8221;) was granted on January 1 of each year to each outside director for each committee of the Board on which had served as a chairperson for at least six months.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3644 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 76.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3645 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Options granted under the Directors Plan generally had a term of 10 years. One-third of the shares were exercisable after the first year and thereafter one-third at the end of each twelve-month period.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3646 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 76.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3647 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Directors Plan expired in January 2014 and therefore no further awards may be granted thereunder. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2,464,933 shares of common stock had been granted under the plan and stock options to acquire 495,000 shares remained outstanding in the plan prior to its expiration.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA94.1 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<P ID=PARA313 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; MARGIN: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	U.S. dollars in thousands, except share and per share data.
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
</FONT>
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P ID=PARA3649 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	1998 Non-Officer Employee Stock Option Plan
</B>
<B>
	(1998 Plan)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3650 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3651 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	In 1998, the Company adopted the 1998 Plan. Under the 1998 Plan, employees may be granted non-qualified stock options for the purchase of common stock. The 1998 Plan currently provides for the purchase of up to 5,062,881 shares of common stock. As of December 31, 2015, 35,473 shares of common stock remained available for grant under the 1998 Plan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3652 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3653 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The exercise price of options under the 1998 Plan shall not be less than the fair market value of common stock for nonqualified stock options, as determined by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors or a committee appointed by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3654 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3655 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Options under the 1998 Plan are generally exercisable over a 48-month period beginning 12 months after issuance, or as determined by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors or a committee appointed by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors. Options under the 1998 Plan expire up to seven years after the date of grant.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3656 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;

<P ID=PARA3657 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	2001 Stock Incentive Plan
</B>
<B>
	(2001 Plan)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3658 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3659 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	In 2001, the Company adopted the 2001 Plan. The 2001 Plan expired in 2011 and no further grants of awards may be made thereunder. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2,194,847 shares of common stock were granted under the plan, stock options to acquire 10,000 shares remained outstanding in the plan prior to its expiration.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3660 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3661 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The 2001 Plan authorized the administrator to grant incentive stock options at an exercise price of not less than 100% of the fair market value of the common stock on the date the option is granted.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3662 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3663 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Equity awards under the 2001 Plan were generally exercisable over a 48-month period beginning 12 months after issuance or as determined by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors or a committee appointed by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors. Equity awards under the 2001 plan expired up to seven years after the date of grant.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3664 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3665 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	2003 Israeli Share Incentive Plan
</B>
<B>
	(2003 Plan)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3666 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3667 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	In 2003, the Company adopted the 2003 Plan, which complied with the Israeli tax reforms. The 2003 Plan terminated in 2012 upon approval of the Company&#8217;s 2012 Equity Incentive Plan (the &#8220;2012 Plan&#8221;). As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, 10,700,543 shares of common stock had been granted under the plan and stock option and SARs to acquire 922,595 shares of common stock remained outstanding under the plan. As the 2003 Plan expired in May 2012, no further awards may be granted thereunder.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3668 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<P ID=PARA3669 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Equity awards under the 2003 Plan were generally exercisable over a 48-month period beginning 12 months after issuance, or as determined by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors or a committee appointed by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors. Equity awards under the 2003 Plan expired up to seven years after the date of grant.
</FONT>

<P ID=PARA95.2 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">

<P ID=PARA312 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; MARGIN: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	U.S. dollars in thousands, except share and per share data.
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
</FONT>
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P ID=PARA3671 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	2012 Equity Incentive Plan
</B>
<B>
	(2012 Plan)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3672 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3673 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	In 2012, the Company adopted the 2012 Plan, which also complies with the Israeli tax reforms. Under the 2012 Plan, employees, directors and consultants may be granted incentive or non-qualified stock options, SARs, RSUs and other awards under the plan. The exercise price of the equity awards under the 2012 Plan shall not be less than the fair market value of common stock at the time of grant, unless otherwise determined by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors or a committee appointed by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors. The 2012 Plan currently provides for the purchase of up to 2,450,000 shares of common stock. As of December 31, 2015, 1,027,577 shares of common stock remained available for grant under the 2012 Plan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3674 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3675 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Stock options, SARs and RSUs awarded under the 2012 Plan to employees and executive officers are generally exercisable over a 48-month period beginning 12 months after issuance, or as determined by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors or a committee appointed by the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors Equity awards under the 2012 Plan expire up to seven years after the date of grant.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3676 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3677 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	A director subplan was established under the 2012 Plan to provide for the grant of equity awards to the Company&#8217;s non-employee directors. The director subplan is designed to work automatically; however, to the extent administration is necessary, it would be provided by the Company&#8217;s board of directors. Starting in 2014, non-employee directors are granted automatically under the director subplan, on January 1 of each year, 8,000 stock options and 4,000 restricted stock units, all of which would fully vest at the end of one year from the grant date. If a director is appointed for a term commencing during a calendar year, the director would be granted stock options and restricted stock units on the date of appointment and the number of stock options and restricted stock units granted would be based upon the number of days remaining in the in the calendar year following the date such person was nominated as a director. Solely with respect to calendar year 2014, in addition to the grants of 8,000 stock options and 4,000 restricted stock units on January 1, 2014 to all then elected board members, each committee chair also received an automatic grant of stock options of 15,000 shares.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3678 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3679 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	1993 Employee Stock Purchase Plan (ESPP)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3680 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3681 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 56.7PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Upon the closing of the Company&#8217;s initial public offering, the Company adopted the ESPP. The Company has reserved an aggregate of 4,800,000 shares of common stock for issuance under the ESPP. The ESPP provides that substantially all employees of the Company may purchase Company common stock at 85% of its fair market value on specified dates via payroll deductions. There were approximately 233,000, 310,000 and 374,000 shares of common stock issued at a weighted average purchase price of $7.59, $5.55 and $4.44 per share under the ESPP in 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively. As of December 31, 2015, 1,170,000 shares of common stock were reserved under the ESPP.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3682 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 76.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	SAR grants made prior to January 1, 2009 are convertible for a maximum number of shares of the Company&#8217;s common stock equal to 50% of the SAR units subject to the grant. SAR grants made on or after January 1, 2009 and before January 1, 2010 are convertible for a maximum number of shares of the Company&#8217;s common stock equal to 75% of the SAR units subject to the grant. SAR grants made on or after January 1, 2010 are convertible for a maximum number of shares of the Company&#8217;s common stock equal to 66.67% of the SAR units subject to the grant. SAR grants made on or after January 1, 2012 are convertible for a maximum number of shares of the Company&#8217;s common stock equal to 50% of the SAR units subject to the grant.
</FONT>

</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3939 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The risk-free interest rate assumption is based on U.S. treasury bill interest rates appropriate for the term of the Company&#8217;s employee equity-based awards.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3940 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3941 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The dividend yield assumption is based on the Company&#8217;s historical and expectation of future dividend payouts and may be subject to substantial change in the future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3942 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3943 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The expected term of employee equity-based awards represents the weighted-average period the awards are expected to remain outstanding and is a derived output of the binomial model. The expected life of employee equity-based awards is impacted by all of the underlying assumptions used in the Company&#8217;s model. The binomial model assumes that employees&#8217; exercise behavior is a function of the award&#8217;s remaining contractual life and the extent to which the award is in-the-money (i.e., the average stock price during the period is above the strike price of the award). The binomial model estimates the probability of exercise as a function of these two variables based on the history of exercises and cancellations on past award grants made by the Company.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3944 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3945 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	As equity-based compensation expense recognized in the consolidated statement of operations is based on awards ultimately expected to vest, it should be reduced for estimated forfeitures. The forfeitures are estimated at the time of grant and revised, if necessary, in subsequent periods if actual forfeitures differ from those estimates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3946 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3947 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Pre and post-vesting forfeitures were estimated based on historical experience.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3948 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3949 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The fair value for rights to purchase shares of common stock under the Company&#8217;s ESPP was estimated on each enrollment date using the same assumptions set forth above for the years ended 2015, 2014 and 2013 except the expected life and the volatility. The expected life was assumed to be between six to 24 months based on the contractual life of the plan, and the expected volatility was assumed to be in a range of 22.83%-34.53% in 2015, 29.06%-37.17% in 2014 and 36.37%-44.19% in 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3950 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA3951 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 85.05PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company&#8217;s aggregate equity compensation expenses for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013 totaled $5,092, $5,359 and $4,159, respectively. The Company recognized no tax benefit in its consolidated statements of operations for the years ended December 31, 2015, 2014 and 2013 for the Company&#8217;s equity-based compensation arrangements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA350.1 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company and its subsidiaries lease certain equipment and facilities under non-cancelable operating leases. The Company has significant leased facilities in Herzliya Pituach, Israel. The lease agreement for the Israeli facilities is effective until November 2018. The Company leases its facilities in the U.S. under a contract which terminates in 2018. The Company&#8217;s subsidiaries in Scotland, Japan, Germany, China and Hong-Kong have lease agreements for their facilities that terminate in 2019, 2016, 2016, 2016 and 2016, respectively. The Company&#8217;s subsidiary in India has a lease agreement which terminates in 2020. The Company has operating lease agreements for its motor vehicles which terminate in 2016 through 2018.
</FONT>

	&nbsp;

</P>
<TABLE ID=MTAB4009 STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF; WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-INDENT: 0PX" CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 57PT">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 29PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
<P ID=PARA4010 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	b.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
<P ID=PARA4011 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company participated in programs (most of which are royalty bearing grants) sponsored by the Israeli government for the support of research and development activities. Through December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company had obtained grants from the Israeli Office of the Chief Scientist (the &#8220;OCS&#8221;) for certain of the Company&#8217;s research and development projects. The Company is obligated to pay royalties to the OCS, amounting to 5% of the sales of the products and other related revenues (based on the dollar) generated from such projects, up to 100% of the grants received. The royalty payment obligations also bear interest at the LIBOR rate. The obligation to pay these royalties is contingent on actual sales of the applicable products and in the absence of such sales, no payment is required.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P ID=PARA4012 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV ID=PGBK101 STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0PT; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0PT">
<DIV ID=PGFTR101 STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER">
	&nbsp;
</DIV>
<DIV ID=PGNUM101 STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER">
	-91-
</DIV>
<HR STYLE="HEIGHT: 2PX; WIDTH: 100%; PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS; COLOR: #000000" NOSHADE>
<A NAME="eolPage94"></A>
<DIV ID=PGHDR101 STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT">
	&nbsp;
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P ID=PARA101.2 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA306 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; MARGIN: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	U.S. dollars in thousands, except share and per share data.
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P ID=PARA4013 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 84.3PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, the aggregate contingent liability to the OCS amounted to $7,880. The Israeli Research and Development Law provides that know-how developed under an approved research and development program may not be transferred to third parties without the approval of the OCS.&nbsp;&nbsp;Such approval is not required for the sale or export of any products resulting from such research or development.&nbsp;&nbsp;The OCS, under special circumstances, may approve the transfer of OCS-funded know-how outside Israel, in the following cases: (a) the grant recipient pays to the OCS a portion of the sale price paid in consideration for such OCS-funded know-how or in consideration for the sale of the grant recipient itself, as the case may be, which portion will not exceed six times the amount of the grants received plus interest (or three times the amount of the grant received plus interest, in the event that the recipient of the know-how has committed to retain the R&amp;D activities of the grant recipient in Israel after the transfer); (b) the grant recipient receives know-how from a third party in exchange for its OCS-funded know-how; (c) such transfer of OCS-funded know-how arises in connection with certain types of cooperation in research and development activities; or (d) if such transfer of know-how arises in connection with a liquidation by reason of insolvency or receivership of the grant recipient.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA4015 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<P ID=PARA104.2 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA303 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; MARGIN: 0PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
<B>
	U.S. dollars in thousands, except share and per share data.
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P ID=PARA4215 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 54PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	(1) The amount in 2015 is after a deduction of $207,405 carryforward tax losses of a foreign subsidiary that expired by December 31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA4216 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA4217 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 54PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	Management believes that part of the deferred tax assets will not be realized based on current levels of future taxable income and potentially refundable taxes. Accordingly, a valuation allowance in the amount of $7,577 and $33,115 was recognized as of December 31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA4218 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA4219 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 54PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	As of December 31, 2015, the Company had cash and cash equivalents, marketable securities and time deposits of approximately $121.7&nbsp;million. Out of total cash, cash equivalents and marketable securities of $121.7 million, $107.8 million was held by foreign subsidiaries of the Company. The Company intends to permanently reinvest earnings of its foreign operations and its current operating plans do not demonstrate a need to repatriate foreign earnings to fund the Company&#8217;s U.S. operations. However, if these funds were needed for the Company&#8217;s operations in the United States, the Company would be required to accrue and pay U.S. taxes as well as taxes in other countries to repatriate these funds. The determination of the amount of additional taxes related to the repatriation of these earnings is not practicable, as it may vary based on various factors such as the location of the cash and the effect of regulation in the various jurisdictions from which the cash would be repatriated.
</FONT>
</P>

<P ID=PARA4251 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">

	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<P ID=PARA4250 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 84.25PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The total amount of net unrecognized tax benefits that, if recognized, would affect the effective tax rate was $1,711 and $1,031 at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. The Company accrues interest and penalties relating to unrecognized tax benefits in its provision for income taxes. At December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, the Company had accrued interest and penalties related to unrecognized tax benefits of $180 and $135, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA4252 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">

</FONT>

<P ID=PARA4253 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 84.25PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company reversed income tax contingency reserves that were determined to be no longer required due to the expiration of applicable statute of limitations. Pursuant to this reversal, the Company recorded a tax benefit of $284 during 2013. During 2014, the Company recorded a tax benefit of $858 due to the finalization of a tax assessment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA4254 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PT; MARGIN-TOP: 0PT">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA4255 STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; MARGIN: 0PT 0PT 0PT 84.25PT; LINE-HEIGHT: 1.25">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-FAMILY: TIMES NEW ROMAN, TIMES, SERIF">
	The Company and certain of its subsidiaries file income tax returns in the U.S. federal jurisdiction and various state and foreign jurisdictions. The last examination conducted by U.S. tax authorities was with respect to the Company&#8217;s U.S. federal income tax returns for 2004. The statute of limitations relating to the Company&#8217;s consolidated Federal income tax return is closed for all tax years up to and including 2011.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ID=PARA105.1 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">

<P ID=PARA105.2 STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0PX; MARGIN-TOP: 0PX">

	&nbsp;
</FONT>
